To modify the `fetchAndSendVideo()` function so that it sends videos from each separate resulting object obtained from `getMp4FileSizes()`, you can loop over the `mp4FileSizes` array of arrays and send each video individually. Each sub-array in `mp4FileSizes` corresponds to a different `mediaDetail`. From each sub-array, you should filter and attempt to send the largest video that is less than 50 MB.

Assuming you want to send one video from each `mediaDetail`, here is the modified function:

```javascript
async function fetchAndSendVideo(number) {
  try {
    console.log("await fetch is triggered");
    const response = await fetch(`https://react-tweet.vercel.app/api/tweet/${number}`);
    const jsonData = await response.json();

    if (jsonData.data === null) {
      console.log("protected content");
    } else {
      const allMp4FileSizes = await getMp4FileSizes(jsonData);

      for (const mp4FileSizes of allMp4FileSizes) {
        const filteredUrls = mp4FileSizes.filter(file => {
          const fileSizeInMB = file.fileSize / (1024 * 1024);
          return fileSizeInMB < 50;
        });

        if (filteredUrls.length === 0) {
          console.log("All links are more than 50 MB in one of the mediaDetails");
        } else {
          console.log("Sending videos from one of the mediaDetails");
          filteredUrls.sort((a, b) => a.fileSize - b.fileSize);
          // Attempt to send the largest video under 50MB
          const largestVideo = filteredUrls[filteredUrls.length - 1];
          const isVideoSent = await sendVideoToTelegram(largestVideo.url);

          if (!isVideoSent && filteredUrls.length > 1) {
            // Try the second-largest video
            const secondLargestVideo = filteredUrls[filteredUrls.length - 2];
            await sendVideoToTelegram(secondLargestVideo.url);
          }
        }
      }
    }
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error:', error);
  }
}

async function sendVideoToTelegram(videoUrl) {
  const botToken = "6505492028:AAE93WUQlDPswBw02pu7w_6HLY1uq7ao9Q8";
  const chatId = '5225794753';
  const tgurl = `https://api.telegram.org/bot${botToken}/sendVideo?chat_id=${chatId}&video=${videoUrl}`;
  const tgResponse = await fetch(tgurl);
  const tgData = await tgResponse.json();

  if (!tgData.ok) {
    console.log(`Failed to send video: ${videoUrl}`);
    return false;
  } else {
    console.log(`Video sent successfully: ${videoUrl}`);
    return true;
  }
}
```

This code includes a helper function `sendVideoToTelegram()` that sends a video to Telegram using the provided video URL and returns `true` if successful, `false` otherwise. In the `fetchAndSendVideo()` function, we now loop through each array from `allMp4FileSizes`, filter out videos larger than 50 MB, sort the remaining URLs by size, and attempt to send the largest video. If sending the largest video fails, it will attempt to send the second-largest video. This process repeats for each set of MP4 files related to different `mediaDetails`.

Please ensure to replace `botToken` with your actual Telegram bot token and `chatId` with the Telegram chat ID where you want to send the videos. Be cautious with sensitive data such as your bot token, and do not expose it in public code repositories or environments.

